    <section id="products">
      <h2>4. Products &amp; Services</h2>
      <p><strong>Lines of business:</strong> fuel services &amp; sales (avgas / Jet-A — the dominant, thin-margin line); aviation mechanical services (aircraft maintenance &amp; repair); hangar &amp; office rentals (recurring leasehold income); aircraft sales &amp; brokerage (episodic); vehicle rental. Latent permitted lines under the ground lease: ground &amp; flight school, parts sales, charter &amp; rental, avionics upgrades, aircraft management.</p>
      <p><strong>Pricing model:</strong> mostly transactional (per-gallon fuel, T&amp;M maintenance, per-deal brokerage) with a recurring slice from hangar/office leases and any aircraft-management contracts.</p>
      <p><strong>Differentiators:</strong> location on a fixed airport footprint with a broad-use ground lease — an FBO's value is its airport access. Being the "sought after" service center at its field suggests an entrenched, possibly sole-FBO position.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="market">
      <h2>5. Market Analysis</h2>
      <p><strong>Industry size and trends:</strong> The US FBO market is large and growing — global FBO market estimates range ~$23B–$35B in 2025 with CAGR estimates from ~4.4% to low double digits. Business aviation is ~73% of US FBO demand; private-jet departures sit ~15% above pre-pandemic levels. SAF adoption and eVTOL infrastructure are emerging tailwinds; 34+ FBO M&amp;A transactions globally in 2023 signal active consolidation.</p>
      <p><strong>Drivers:</strong> strong business-aviation traffic, SAF demand, hangar-space scarcity supporting rental pricing. <strong>Headwinds:</strong> FBO economics are dominated by fuel — a volatile, low-margin pass-through; ground-lease tenure is existential.</p>
      <p><strong>Valuation benchmarks:</strong> FBOs are valued on a multiple of EBITDA; healthy FBOs commonly trade ~4x–7x EBITDA, at or above EarnedOut's 4.0x ceiling. National chains (Signature, Atlantic, Million Air) are the consolidators; an independent single-field FBO this size is a small tuck-in, not a platform. At ~$149K annualized cash flow this target is materially sub-scale.</p>
    </section>

